  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations through FY2026 to date total $474B. The Department of Defense leads all agencies with $239B in obligations, followed by the Department of Homeland Security at $52B and the Department of Veterans Affairs at $51.1B. The Department of Energy reported $45.7B, the General Services Administration $18.6B, and the Department of Health and Human Services $13.5B. Smaller but still material obligations were recorded by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration at $9.5B, the Department of Transportation at $8.7B, and both the Department of Agriculture and the Department of Justice at $6.3B each. These figures reflect obligations to date in FY2026 and present the raw contract spending totals by agency without single-year allocation adjustments. The distribution shows a clear dollar concentration at the top of the ranking while multiple civilian agencies also record multibillion-dollar obligations. Contracting officers and industry partners can use these totals to prioritize engagement and align capability offers with agencies that report the largest absolute contract obligations in FY2026 to date.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies lead federal contract obligations in FY2026 to date?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense leads with $239B in obligations. The Department of Homeland Security follows with $52B and the Department of Veterans Affairs reports $51.1B. The Department of Energy is next at $45.7B, with the General Services Administration at $18.6B and the Department of Health and Human Services at $13.5B."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How do other major civilian agencies compare on contract obligations?",
        "body": "NASA recorded $9.5B in obligations and the Department of Transportation recorded $8.7B. The Department of Agriculture and the Department of Justice each reported $6.3B. These figures are the reported obligations for FY2026 to date out of a total $474B in obligations."
      }
    ]
  },
